lla-La Mancha, Spanje","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanje","Spain":"Spanje"},"en":{"–1160":"–1160","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1129–Male":"1129–Deceased","1160–1217":"1160–1217","–1260":"–1260","–1261":"–1261","1129":"1129","1217":"1217","about 1160":"about 1160","1159":"1159","despues del 4 de febrero de 1159":"4 February 1159","1100":"1100","1261":"1261","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Spain":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"En","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 鄧, see   Deng   1.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 丁, see   Ding   1.","Chinese: possibly also from Taishanese form of the Chinese name 進 (meaning ‘progress’), a monosyllabic personal name or part of a disyllabic personal name of some early Chinese immigrants in the US."],"variants":[{"name":"Deng","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Hua, Jian, Jing, Wei, Wen, Yi, Ying, Chao, Fang, Gang, Hui, Min.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 鄧: (i) from Deng (鄧), the name of a state (located in Dengxian in Henan province) granted to Man Ji, uncle of Wu Ding (a king of the Shang dynasty (1600 –1046  BC )). (ii) from Deng Bowen (鄧伯溫), head of an ancient state (located in present-day Shandong province) dating back to the reign of the legendary Huang Di, the ‘Yellow Emperor’ (<i>c.</i> 27th century  BC ). (iii) from Deng (鄧), a fief (located in Hubei province) granted to descendants of Zhong Kang, the 4th king of the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC ). (iv) from Deng Cheng (鄧城, City of Deng), a town in the state of Cai (located in present-day Henan province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (v) from Deng (鄧), a title of Li Tianyi, the 8th son of Li Yu (the last king of the state of Southern Tang (937–975  AD ) during the Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms (907–960) periods). The state of Southern Tang was annexed by Emperor Taizong of Song (939–997  AD ) in 975  AD , and the royal families of South Tang were hunted down. Li Tianyi's son fled and changed the surname (Li) to Deng (鄧), his father's title."]}]},{"name":"Blanco","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Juan, Carlos, Jorge, Luis, Raul, Francisco, Miguel, Julio, Pedro, Jesus.","Spanish: nickname for a man with white or fair hair or a pale complexion, from <i>blanco</i> ‘white’.","Italian (Sicily): variant of   Bianco  , perhaps influenced by French <i>blanc</i> or Spanish <i>blanco</i> (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bianco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Angelo, Salvatore, Carmine, Antonio, Rocco, Aniello, Francesco, Luca, Luigi, Pasquale, Sal.","Italian: from <i>bianco</i> ‘white’ (of ancient Germanic origin; compare Old High German <i>blanc</i> ‘bright, shining, white, beautiful’), originally applied as a nickname for a man with white or fair hair or a pale complexion, or for someone who habitually wore white, especially in jousting or other competitions, and later used as a personal name. Compare   Lo Bianco  ."]},{"name":"Blanca","meanings":["Spanish: from the feminine form of   Blanco   ‘white’."]}]},{"name":"Dama","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly North American: of unknown origin, perhaps a transferred use of a surname that is fairly common in the United States. This may be of Irish origin, although the surname is not known in Ireland. <i>Dana</i> or <i>Ana</i> was the name of an ancient Irish fertility goddess, and this was also used in medieval times as a girl's name, However, it is not clear whether there is any connection between this name and the modern given name, which is sometimes also used as a feminine form of   Dan   or   Daniel .  Modern use as a boy's given name began in honour of  Richard Henry Dana  (  1815–82 ), author of Two Years before the Mast, who supported the rights of fugitive slaves before and during the Civil War. The popularity of the given name was increased by the fame of the film star  Dana Andrews  (  1909–92 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Dama En Blanco had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Ermildo Meléndez. She died in 1160, in Spain."},"et":{"–1160":"–1160","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1129–Male":"1129–Surnud","1160–1217":"1160–1217","–1260":"–1260","–1261":"–1261","1129":"1129","1217":"1217","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1159":"1159","despues del 4 de febrero de 1159":"4. veebruar 1159","1100":"1100","1261":"1261","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Spain":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"–1160":"–1160","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1129–Male":"1129–Kuollut","1160–1217":"1160–1217","–1260":"–1260","–1261":"–1261","1129":"1129","1217":"1217","about 1160":"noin 1160","1159":"1159","despues del 4 de febrero de 1159":"4. helmikuuta 1159","1100":"1100","1261":"1261","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanja","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanja","Spain":"Espanja"},"fr":{"–1160":"–1160","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1129–Male":"1129–Décédé","1160–1217":"1160–1217","–1260":"–1260","–1261":"–1261","1129":"1129","1217":"1217","about 1160":"environ 1160","1159":"1159","despues del 4 de febrero de 1159":"4 février 1159","1100":"1100","1261":"1261","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espagne","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espagne","Spain":"Espagne","lifeSummar